            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old male who presents to the gastroenterology clinic with a several-week history of persistent epigastric discomfort, postprandial bloating, and intermittent nausea. He describes the pain as a dull, gnawing ache in the upper abdomen that worsens after meals, particularly following spicy foods or a glass of whiskey. He occasionally experiences early satiety, a sour taste in his mouth, and episodes of excessive belching after eating, which he initially dismissed as \"just stress.\" Over the past two weeks, he has also reported two episodes of vomiting, typically occurring in the morning or after a heavy evening meal. His appetite has markedly diminished — he has been deliberately avoiding food because the anticipation of eating triggers significant discomfort, and he has lost several kilograms over the past month due to this pronounced reduction in food intake. His wife has become alarmed by how little he is eating, noting that he sometimes goes entire days consuming only coffee. On examination, he appears mildly fatigued but is in no acute distress. His abdomen is soft with mild tenderness on deep palpation in the epigastric region. No guarding or rebound tenderness is noted.\n\n{patientName} works as a mid-level manager at a logistics company, a role he has held for nearly 15 years. His job is high-pressure and deadline-driven, often requiring him to skip lunch or eat hurriedly at his desk. He frequently travels for work and relies heavily on fast food, restaurant meals, and processed snacks. He admits to drinking 3–4 cups of strong black coffee daily and consuming alcohol socially 3–4 times per week, typically 2–3 drinks per occasion.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys watching football, occasional weekend fishing trips with friends, and tinkering with vintage cars in his garage. His fishing hobby involves long hours outdoors with minimal food breaks — he often skips meals or snacks on highly processed crackers, chips, and energy drinks during these trips, habits that aggravate his gastric mucosa. Similarly, during his garage sessions restoring vintage cars, he frequently snacks on greasy takeaway food and drinks multiple cans of cola or energy drinks, compounding his caffeine and acid load. He smokes about half a pack of cigarettes per day — a habit he has maintained for roughly 25 years — and has made several unsuccessful attempts to quit. He gets limited physical exercise, describing himself as \"mostly sedentary\" during the workweek.\n\n{patientName} lives with his wife of 28 years in a suburban home. They have two adult children who live nearby. He describes his home life as generally supportive, though he acknowledges that work stress spills over and affects his mood and sleep. He sleeps approximately 5–6 hours per night and often wakes with heartburn, sometimes needing to prop himself up with pillows to get back to sleep.\n\nHe initially delayed seeking medical attention, attributing his symptoms to \"getting older,\" but was prompted to visit after his wife noticed he had significantly reduced his food intake over the past month due to the discomfort — at times refusing meals altogether, consistent with a marked anorexic pattern driven by pain avoidance. He denies any hematemesis, melena, or unintentional weight loss exceeding 3 kg over the past six months."
